The paper deals with the complexity of sampling from the set of partitions of a planar graph into connected components, which involves topics such as graph theory, computational complexity, and algorithms. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also discusses the flip walk Markov chain used in practice for this sampling task, which falls under the category of computational complexity (cs.CC). The use of gadgets and empirical evidence to demonstrate slow mixing of the flip walk suggests a connection to graph theory (cs.GT) and simulation (cs.SI). Finally, the paper mentions applications to political redistricting, which could fall under the category of computational geometry (cs.CG).
